e officially inscribed in public space, while others are visible only through alternative, ephemeral or subversive means. Including discussions of the history of the Red Location Museum of Struggle; memorialisation of urban forced removals; the heritage politics and transformative potential of public art; and strategies for making visible memories and histories of former anti-apartheid youth activist groups in the city’s townships, Roux examines how these twin processes of memory-making and change have played out in Nelson Mandela Bay.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 06. Mrz 2024) 0aCommunity development, UrbanzSouth Africa. 0aPost-apartheid erazSouth Africa. 0aUrban policyzSouth Africa. 7aHISTORY / Africa / South / Republic of South Africa.2bisacsh  aNelson Mandela Bay.  aPort Elizabeth.  acollective memory.  acommunity museums.  amemorial architecture.  apost-apartheid memorialisation.  apost-apartheid museums.  apublic architecture.  aurban heritage.  aurban transformation.1 aRoux, Naomi, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertManchester University Press 2021 eBook-Packagez978311128198840uhttps://doi.org/10.7765/978152614029640uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9781526140296423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9781526140296/original  a978-3-11-128198-8  Manchester University Press 2021 eBook-Packageb2021  aGBV-deGruyter-alles